/*
Problem: Lower Bound

Definition:
Return the index of the first element greater than or equal to x.
If no such element exists, return n.

Approach:
1. Initialize answer as n.
2. Apply Binary Search.
3. If nums[mid] >= x:
   - Store mid as a potential answer.
   - Search on the left side for a smaller valid index.
4. Otherwise, search on the right side.
5. Return the answer.

Time Complexity: O(log N)
Space Complexity: O(1)
*/

class Solution {
public:
    int lowerBound(vector<int> &nums, int x) {
        int n = nums.size();
        int st = 0;
        int end = n - 1;
        int ans = n;

        while (st <= end) {
            int mid = st + (end - st) / 2;

            if (nums[mid] >= x) {
                ans = mid;
                end = mid - 1;
            } else {
                st = mid + 1;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};

/*
Mistakes I Made While Learning:

1. Used:
   while(st >= end)
   Correct:
   while(st <= end)

2. Compared:
   if(mid == x)
   Correct:
   if(nums[mid] >= x)

3. Used:
   end--;
   Correct:
   end = mid - 1;
   (Discard the entire right half, not just one element.)

4. Used:
   st++;
   Correct:
   st = mid + 1;
   (Discard the entire left half.)

5. Initialized answer with:
   INT_MIN / INT_MAX
   Better:
   ans = n;
   (If no lower bound exists, insertion position is n.)

6. Used:
   ans = min(ans, mid);
   Better:
   ans = mid;
   (Since we're already searching on the left, the latest valid mid is always a better candidate.)

7. Used wrong variable names:
   a[mid], i
   Correct:
   nums[mid], x

Key Binary Search Rule:
Left Search  -> end = mid - 1;
Right Search -> st = mid + 1;
*/
